│ Understanding the Issue: The issue is that the SLP vectorizer is producing  │
│ incorrect results when vectorizing a sequence of operations involving sign  │
│ extension (sext) and zero extension (zext) instructions. In the reproducer, │
│ we have two similar sequences:\n- One with `sext i16 0 to i32` and `zext    │
│ i16 0 to i32`\n- Another with `sext i16 0 to i32` and `zext i16 -1 to       │
│ i32`\n\nThe vectorizer incorrectly combines these into a single vector      │
│ operation using `<2 x i16> <i16 poison, i16 0>` as the base vector, which   │
│ leads to wrong comparison results. Specifically, the source computes        │
│ `%cmp8.i85.peel.i = icmp slt i32 0, 65535` which should be true (1), but    │
│ the target computes `icmp slt <2 x i16> {0, 0}, {-1, 0}` which gives `{0,   │
│ 0}`, extracting lane 0 gives 0 instead of 1.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log:   │
│ The log shows that the SLP vectorizer identifies a profitable vectorization │
│ opportunity with cost -3 for VF=2. It creates a vector by inserting         │
│ `%sub.i.i79.peel.i` (which is -1) at position 0 into a vector initialized   │
│ with poison and 0. However, the problem is in how the gather function       │
│ handles the type conversion for the operands.\n\nLooking at the debug       │
│ output, the vectorizer is trying to vectorize the compare instructions      │
│ `%cmp8.i85.peel.i` and `%cmp8.i.i`, which have operands of different types  │
│ after extension (one is sext result, another is zext result). The issue     │
│ occurs in the `gather` function where it tries to create a common type for  │
│ insertion.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The root cause is in the              │
│ `CreateInsertElement` lambda within the `gather` function (around line      │
│ 13708). When handling cast instructions (sext/zext), the code attempts to   │
│ optimize by using the source operand directly if it's not part of the tree  │
│ being vectorized. However, this optimization fails to account for the       │
│ semantic difference between sign extension and zero                         │
│ extension.\n\nSpecifically, in lines 13701-13707, the code checks if the    │
│ scalar is a sext or zext instruction, and if the operand is not part of the │
│ current tree, it uses the operand directly (`V = Op`). This is problematic  │
│ because sext and zext have different semantics - they produce different     │
│ results when the source value has its high bit set.\n\nIn our case:\n-      │
│ `%conv7.i84.peel.i = sext i16 0 to i32` → operand is `i16 0`\n-             │
│ `%xor5.i81.peel.i = zext i16 -1 to i32` → operand is `i16 -1`\n\nThe code   │
│ strips both to their `i16` operands and then tries to create a common       │
│ vector type. However, when these are later compared as `i16` values in the  │
│ vectorized form, the comparison `slt` on `<2 x i16> {0, 0}, {-1, 0}` gives  │
│ different results than the original scalar comparisons on the extended      │
│ `i32` values.\n\nThe issue is that the optimization assumes that using the  │
│ source operand directly is equivalent, but this is only true if both        │
│ extensions are of the same type (both sext or both zext) or if the source   │
│ values are known to be non-negative (making sext and zext                   │
│ equivalent).\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\n+ The fix is to remove the      │
│ optimization that strips cast instructions when they are of different types │
│ (sext vs zext) or when the signedness matters for the operation being       │
│ performed. The simplest and safest fix is to disable this optimization      │
│ entirely for mixed sext/zext scenarios, which means not stripping the cast  │
│ when the operand types would lead to semantic differences.\n\nThe           │
│ problematic code is at line 13708 where `CreateIntCast` is called with a    │
│ signedness parameter based on `isKnownNonNegative(Scalar,                   │
│ SimplifyQuery(*DL))`. However, the earlier optimization in lines            │
│ 13701-13707 bypasses this careful signedness handling by directly using the │
│ operand.\n\nBy removing the optimization that sets `V = Op` for cast        │
│ instructions, we ensure that the original cast instructions are preserved   │
│ and handled correctly through the normal intcast path which respects        │
│ signedness.\n\n5. Conclusion: The fix ensures that sext and zext            │
│ instructions are not prematurely stripped during vectorization, preserving  │
│ their semantic differences. This will prevent the incorrect vectorization   │
│ that led to the value mismatch in the reproducer. The vectorizer will       │
│ either handle the casts properly through the intcast mechanism or decide    │
│ not to vectorize the mixed sext/zext sequence, both of which are correct    │
│ behaviors."})                                                               │
